From 5ba916a2feb054041dda3c3b00baed307665f3b8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Tim 'mithro' Ansell <me@mith.ro>
Date: Mon, 6 Apr 2026 23:03:49 +0930
Subject: [PATCH 14/16] Fix GENET RX: use ring 0 as default receive queue

The Linux bcmgenet driver configures HFB filter 0 to direct all
default traffic to ring 0 (not ring 16). It only sets up NAPI
for ring 0 (rx_queues=0 means ring 0 is the only RX ring). The
QEMU GENET code was sending unfiltered packets to ring 16 which
has no NAPI handler, no interrupts, and no descriptors set up.

This was the root cause of Linux ping/DHCP failure: packets were
delivered to the wrong DMA ring.

Result: Full end-to-end Linux networking now works:
  64 bytes from 10.0.2.2: seq=0 ttl=255 time=41.317 ms
  64 bytes from 10.0.2.2: seq=1 ttl=255 time=1.041 ms
  64 bytes from 10.0.2.2: seq=2 ttl=255 time=1.087 ms
  udhcpc: lease of 10.0.2.15 obtained from 10.0.2.2

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 hw/net/bcm2838_genet.c | 8 +++++++-
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/hw/net/bcm2838_genet.c b/hw/net/bcm2838_genet.c
index adc2f459e..6d2080b23 100644
--- a/hw/net/bcm2838_genet.c
+++ b/hw/net/bcm2838_genet.c
@@ -999,7 +999,13 @@ static ssize_t bcm2838_genet_receive(NetClientState *nc, const uint8_t *buf,
         if (filter_index >= 0) {
             ring_index = bcm2838_genet_filter2ring(s, filter_index);
         } else {
-            ring_index = BCM2838_GENET_DMA_RING_CNT - 1;
+            /*
+             * No HFB filter match. The Linux driver configures HFB filter 0
+             * to send all default traffic to ring 0 and only uses ring 0
+             * for RX (with NAPI). Use ring 0 as default when HFB is not
+             * implemented.
+             */
+            ring_index = 0;
         }
 
         if (size <= MAX_PACKET_SIZE) {
